definition.value: Any compound that is able to protect normal cells from the damage caused by radiation therapy.
Any compound which inhibits the postganglionic functioning of the sympathetic nervous system (SNS).
Any compound used to suppress premature labour and immature birth by suppressing uterine contractions.
An N-acyl-L-alpha-amino acid anion obtained by deprotonation of any folic acid.
A L-alpha-amino acid anion which is the conjugate base of L-dopa, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group: major species at pH 7.3.
Any branched-chain fatty acid anion containing methyl branches only.
A folate obtained by deprotonation of any tetrahydrofolic acid.
A carbamate ester that is methyl 1H-benzimidazol-2-ylcarbamate substituted by a benzoyl group at position 5.
A sulfonium betaine that is a conjugate base of S-adenosyl-L-methionine obtained by the deprotonation of the carboxy group.
An agonist that binds to and activates cannabinoid receptors.
Any compound that has anti-inflammatory effects.

An aminobenzoic acid that is anthranilic acid in which one of the hydrogens attached to the nitrogen is replaced by a 2,6-dichloro-3-methylphenyl group. A non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug, it is used as the sodium salt for the treatment of dysmenorrhoea (painful periods), osteoarthritis and rheumatoid arthritis.
A chemosterilant intended to sterilize insects.

A ryanodine receptor modulator which activates the receptor. Ryanodine receptors (RyRs) act as selective ion channels, modulating the release of calcium. Activating the receptors causes the release of calcium, so depleting internal calcium and ultimately preventing further muscle contraction.
A monohydroxyquinoline in which the hydroxy group is positioned at C-8 with a nitro group trans to it at C-5.
Any organphosphate oxoanion resulting from the removal of both protons from the phosphate group of a phosphate monoester. The major species at pH 7.3.
A molecule that can substitute for a normal nucleobase in nucleic acids.
A primary alcohol that is ethanol in which one of the methyl hydrogens is replaced by a morpholin-4-yl group.
A 3-oxo Delta(4)-steroid that is pregn-4-ene-3,20-dione substituted by an alpha-hydroxy group at position 17 and a methyl group at position 6.

An aminobenzoic acid that is anthranilic acid in which one of the hydrogens attached to the nitrogen is replaced by a 2,3-dimethylphenyl group. Although classed as a non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug, its anti-inflammatory properties are considered to be minor. It is used to relieve mild to moderate pain, including headaches, dental pain, osteoarthritis and rheumatoid arthritis.

A diverse group of pharmacologically active secondary metabolite characteristic to Cannabis plant as well as produced naturally in the body by humans and animals. Cannabinoids contain oxygen as a part of the heterocyclic ring or in the form of various functional groups. They are subdivided on the basis of their origin.
A class of cannabinoid which are C21 terpenophenolic compounds isolated primarily from Cannabis sativa.
An agonist that selectively binds to and activates a retinoic acid receptor.
An antogonist that interferes with the action of activator protein 1 (AP-1).
A provitamin that can be converted into vitamin A by enzymes from animal tissues.
A 3-oxo Delta(4)-steroid that is pregna-4,6-diene-3,20-dione substituted by a methyl group at position 6 and a hydroxy group at position 17.
An EC 3.2.1.* (glycosidase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of alpha-glucosidase (EC 3.2.1.20).
A diketone in which the two keto groups are separated by a single carbon atom.
An inhibitor of HIV-1 integrase, an enzyme required for the integration of the genetic material of the retrovirus into the DNA of the infected cells.
Any 1,4-benzoquinone carrying a single hydroxy substituent.

A benzothiazine that is piroxicam in which the pyridin-2-yl group is replaced by a 5-methyl-1,3-thiazol-2-yl group. A non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug and selective inhibitor of COX-2, it is used particularly for the management of rheumatoid arthritis.
A naphthalene-1,4-diol having a methyl substituent at the 2-position.

A piperidinecarboxylate ester that is piperidine which is substituted by a methyl group at position 1 and by phenyl and ethoxycarbonyl groups at position 4. It is an analgesic which is used for the treatment of moderate to severe pain, including postoperative pain and labour pain.

An imidazolidine-2,4-dione (hydantoin) in which the imidazolidine nucleus carries a methyl group at N-3 and has ethyl and phenyl substituents at C-5. An anticonvulsant, it is no longer available in the USA or the UK but is still studied largely because of its interesting hydroxylation polymorphism.
A member of the class of barbiturates, the structure of which is that of barbituric acid substituted at N-1 by a methyl group and at C-5 by ethyl and phenyl groups.
A piperidinecarboxamide in which N-methylpipecolic acid and 2,6-dimethylaniline have combined to form the amide bond. It is used as a local amide-type anaesthetic.

An ethylenediamine derivative that is  ethylenediamine in which one of the amino nitrogens is substituted by two methyl groups and the remaining amino nitrogen is substituted by a 4-methoxybenzyl and a pyridin-2-yl group.

An organic sodium salt that is 2,7-dibromo-4-hydroxymercurifluorescein in which the carboxy group and the phenolic hydroxy group have been deprotonated and the resulting charge is neutralised by two sodium ions.
A monohydroxybenzoic acid that is salicylic acid substituted by an amino group at the 5-position.
A phenothiazine substituted at position 2 (para to the S atom) by a methylsulfinyl group, and on the nitrogen by a 2-(1-methylpiperidin-2-yl)ethyl group.
A terminal acetylenic compound that is (17alpha)-17-ethynylestra-1(10),2,4-triene substituted by a methoxy group at position 3 and a hydroxy group at position 17.
